sentence: Lawrence Lui (135.25) vs.
Rangbo Sulang (135.75) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Sulang (-250), Lui (+190) Round 1 And just like that, combat in a major organization is back in your life again on a Saturday night.
That is, for fans watching stateside.
For the poor, unfortunate souls in Sydney, Australia, today their fight card starts at 9 a.m. at the Qudos Bank Arena.

Before getting to the action that most came here to see, the promotion has to take care of some particularsânamely, three (not four) Road to UFC Finals matches pitting talent from the East Asian and Oceanic regions together to qualify for a spot on the UFC-described overstuffed roster.

The first of those three comes at 135 pounds in a historic matchup between China and Hong Kong where there totally isn't any tertiary drama surrounding that nation and its special administrative region.
We stick to sports this sunny Saturday and get ready to watch Sulang (10-3, 0-0 UFC) and Lui (7-1, 0-0 UFC) collide, with only one man winning the tournament and contract.

Referee Jim Perdios will take it from here, as he stands back while the athletes come together but do not touch gloves. (function (v,i) { let screenWidth = i.innerWidth; if (screenWidth <= 400) { document.getElementById('adViAi').style.display = 'none'; return; } var scp = v.createElement('script'), config = { ChannelID: '0nqr3w5ff', AdUnitType: '2', PublisherID: '256607409443141', PlacementID: 'pltU2JIgmaTXI9XW18z', DivID: '', IAB_Category: 'IAB17', Keywords: '', Language: 'en-us', BG_Color: '', Text_Color: '', Font: '', FontSize: '', }; scp.src='https://s.vi-serve.com/tagLoader.js'; scp.type = 'text/javascript'; scp.async = true; scp.onload = function() { i[btoa('video intelligence start')].init(config); }; (v.getElementsByTagName('head')[0] || v.documentElement.appendChild(v.createElement('head'))).appendChild(scp); })(document, window); Advertisement The fans start wooing immediately, as the 135ers shadowbox before getting to business.
Lui leads off first and backs Sulang off, chasing him with a couple punches before bailing to avoid counters.
He shoots low for a single-leg takedown, elevating the leg high in the air to leverage the Chinese athlete to the mat.
Sulang scrambles to get to his knees, and Lui tosses him back flat again for a moment.
Sulang wall-walks and takes a few knees to the thigh, but Lui is a dog with a bone clutching him from behind doing work on his posterior with additional knees.
Phrasing.
Sulang works his way upright once more, and he breaks the grip and gets away with nary a scratch.
Lui rushes after him, walking face-first into an uppercut and paying it no mind.
Lui pressures forward, forcing Sulang to circle along the cage wall but not cornering him.
Lui lets go with a few punches, and Sulang counters with a crisp uppercut that gets Lui's attention.
The power punches from Sulang force Lui to drop and shoot on another takedown, and this time, Sulang bounces away and lights him up with a few more crisp punches.
Lui stands and gathers his thoughts, and he cracks Sulang with a pair of looping hooks.
Lui gets too reckless, and he gets nailed with a solid uppercut from Sulang to shake him up.
Lui shoots in again, and Sulang times a powerful uppercut to stop him from going any further.
Sulang reaches and dings Lui with a long right, leading to a furious exchange where Lui lets his hands go but largely misses the mark.
Lui uses his swarming attack to grip hold of his foe again, and he drags him to a knee against the wire.
Lui hangs on from behind, narrowly evading a jumping kick from a separating Sulang as the horn blares.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Sulang Brian Knapp scores the round: 10-9 Sulang Tyler Treese scores the round: 10-9 Sulang Round 2 The cutman has to tend to Lui's mouth and nose between rounds, as Sulang's kick may have done a little more damage than he let on.
They get right after it when the second round kicks off, with Lui pushing the action but ultimately swinging and missing with his initial assault.
Lui avoids an uppercut to counter with a forearm strike on the jaw, and Sulang backpedals to get away from any other strikes and the takedown that inevitably comes.
Sulang springs off, and he makes Lui pay for it with three crisp punches.
Lui gets right back on the accelerator with his forward pressure, and he comes up short on most of them as Sulang is away in time.
Sulang plays the matador to Lui's bull, as Lui swings to set something up and manages to clip him with a left hook before shooting deep for a single.
Sulang sprawls effectively and tags Lui on the break, but he does not keep Lui from chasing him down.
Lui dings his man with a pair of shots upstairs, and he strafes when Sulang zips a hook at him.
Sulang times a jumping knee when Lui advances, but it is only a glancing blow.
Lui pitches a kick at the fighter from China, and he makes Sulang ricochet off the wall with his offense.
Lui dodges a hook, and Sulang gives him a few more to think about even if most do not get through the guard.
Lui shakes it off and crashes the pocket for a takedown attempt, and he succeeds in dragging the Enbo Fight Club member to his knees.
Sulang quickly wall-walks to get upright while Lui leans on him, and the weight imposed by "Lok Yin" forces Sulang back down again.
Lui sneaks in punches around the side when not pursuing his level change, and he sells out for a takedown by dragging his own weight as leverage.
Sulang springs back up and they proceed to bang it out for a moment, as he gets the better of the exchange.
Lui is not about to take his foot off the gas, and he even races in with his hands down to get them around Sulang's waist.
Sulang backs him off for a moment with an elbow, and he bloodies Lui back up with a couple strikes before the horn sounds.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Lui Brian Knapp scores the round: 10-9 Lui Tyler Treese scores the round: 10-9 Lui Round 3 The fighters rush towards one another to get started, with Lui going right after the gut with his swings.
Sulang pops him with the jab, and he follows one with a right hand to split the guard.
Lui stands too tall in one exchange, allowing Sulang to nail him with an overhand right.
They trade fists, and Lui tries for a knee to jam up the middle.
Sulang circles away, and he loops a left hand up and over the guard before loading up on a power right.
Lui shrugs them off and stays right in the fighter from China's face, while Sulang gets his jab going further.
The head movement from Sulang allows him to dodge the increasingly wide swings from Lui, who is loading up and getting caught more often.
Lui takes another hook and tries for a knee, and Sulang leans back just in the nick of time.
Lui's pressure works against him as Sulang potshots him, although he can manage another takedown shot that he uses to drag Sulang to his knees.
With Sulang blocking his face, his body and side is wide open, allowing Lui to knee him repeatedly.
Sulang muscles his way up, and Lui pulls him right back down with a hold on Sulang's ankle closes to the fence.
The foot control of Lui allows him to trap Sulang, who is stuck on his hands and knees trying to get out of this frustration situation.
All the while, Lui knees him in the backside, further bruising up his hindquarters from consistent attacks.
The moment Sulang posts off to get up, Lui laces his legs between Sulang's to drag him to the floor.
Sulang gets a moment of success as he forces a reversal of position, only for Lui to demoralizingly keep him in his clutches.
Sulang pulls on the fence a few times to improve his posture, leading to Perdios fussing at him and slapping his hand.
When the 10-second clapper sounds, Sulang points to the ground, and they do proceed to bang it out until time expires.
Lui, expecting victory, climbs on top of the cage to signal to the crowd that he thinks he got the job done.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Lui (29-28 Lui) Brian Knapp scores the round: 10-9 Lui (29-28 Lui) Tyler Treese scores the round: 10-9 Lui (29-28 Lui) The Official Result Lawrence Lui def.
Rangbo Sulang via Split Decision (29-28, 28-29, 29-28)
Keiichiro Nakamura (145.25) vs.

Sebastian Szalay (145.75) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Szalay (-120), Nakamura (-106) Round 1 We move right along to the next tourney final, which officially counts for us as the first UFC fight on their respective careersâthink of it like TUF finals.
From Japan, Nakamura (7-1, 0-0 UFC) will take on relative local Szalay (10-1, 0-0 UFC), even if "Seb" is from Perth all the way across the island nation.
Someone's one (loss) is about to turn into two, barring some unexpected happening, and referee Herb Dean is here for it.
The athletes clap hands before engaging.
Szalay quickly says hello with a body kick, and Nakamura says two can play that game and proceeds to whip four kicks at him in rapid succession.
Szalay tries to counter the fourth, and he loops a left hand over the top.
Both fighters remain just far enough apart to whiff on their kicks, but they are closing in on one another with their strike attempts.
Szalay chains a high kick to a spinning kick, and Nakamura dances out of the way and fires back with a kick that gets blocked up top.
Szalay threatens with his leg before darting in with a trio of punches, and Nakamura is evasive and looks to give back to Szalay every time the Aussie kicks at him.
Szalay just misses on a pouncing left hook, and Nakamura bounds off the fencing and appears to take a sigh of relief that he dodged that one.
Szalay springs back and forth as the crowd grows a bit restless, and he suddenly surges forth to a wheel kick that drills Nakamura right in the face.
Nakamura does not appear compromised, as he goes low with a kick and then gets countered.
Szalay drops his man to a knee with a short combo, and he reaches out and clips Nakamura again with long, sweeping hooks.
Nakamura nearly kicks his foe's leg out, and Szalay's front leg is showing some redness and welting three minutes in.
Szalay keeps kicking with his front leg despite this, slapping Nakamura's calf and then spinning but missing with his wheel kick effort.
Szalay keeps peppering with kicks like jabs, and his hooks largely come up short with Nakamura's footwork keeping him out of the worst danger.
They clash legs at the same time, and Szalay even offers out a hook kick.
The punches from Szalay lead to a spin kick, and Nakamura does not flinch during the oncoming fire.
Szalay chains punches to the side, and he keeps his guard to block a kick aimed at his upper chest.
Szalay ducks and fires off a left, and Nakamura gives him a one-two to think about.
Szalay is quick to raise up his counter knee, and the tow trade punches and one kick as the buzzer sounds.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Szalay Brian Knapp scores the round: 10-9 Szalay Tyler Treese scores the round: 10-9 Szalay Round 2 Hands are clapped before fists fly, but it does not take more than a couple seconds for Szalay to do just that.
Nakamura stays on his bike, evasive and elusive to get away from what flies at him, but Szalay tracks him down and knocks him into the wall.
Nakamura rebounds and checks a low kick, and he pins Szalay down with a one-two.
Szalay darts at him with his own two-punch combo and makes Nakamura have to shake it off, only for Szalay to keep after him and knock him to his seat.
Nakamura springs off the mat and backs off, his volume through the floor while Szalay is landing when he sees fit.
Nakamura tries for his own spinning wheel kick, and Szalay grabs him mid-spin and chucks him to the ground like two armfuls of groceries when you want to make just one trip from the car.
Nakamura leaps back upright, and he leans directly into Szalay's head as a clacking sound echoes through the cage.
Szalay landed a few punches when swarming forward, but after a minute pause, Nakamura clears out the cobwebs and is good to continue.
No harm done, and no ill will from the accidental collision.
Nakamura chambers and fires a kick, and he gets clipped again by the Aussie.
Nakamura fires right back with a few punches to reestablish himself, and he does not make the advancing Szalay falter.
Instead, Szalay knocks him back a few steps, and he stands firm when Nakamura leaps at him with an elbow.
Szalay claims the center of the cage and spins with a whiffing wheel kick, and he calms himself to unload with his fists to the head and body.
Nakamura tries to counter, but he is a day late and a dollar short.
Nakamura's intercepting knee leads to Szalay punching him upside the dome, and he lifts it up a few more times to try to get Szalay coming forward.
An uncalled foul is apologized for from Szalay, as Nakamura wipes his eye and then fires off a couple punches.
Nakamura's jump knee becomes more telegraphed, and he narrowly evades a huge pair of punches before the round concludes.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Szalay Brian Knapp scores the round: 10-9 Szalay Tyler Treese scores the round: 10-9 Szalay Round 3 The 145ers get right to it when the final round kicks off, both men hurling punches that lead to kicks.
The kicks miss the mark, but Szalay is able to catch Nakamura standing still with a combination.
The two slam together like a child playing with action figures, with their collisions stemming from a few punches and plenty of forward movement.
Nakamura gains a full head of steam and rings Szalay's bell with big hooks, and he starts to back Szalay off with his strikes.
Nakamura just misses on a leading elbow, and Szalay is able to counter him effectively.
The fighter from Japan loops a left hand over the guard, but it is one-and-done as they proceed to bang into each other.
Nakamura draws blood on the corner of Szalay's right eye, and Szalay is starting to slow and retreat while Nakamura is dead-set on tracking him down and tagging him with an elbow.
Nakamura follows up on the elbow with a stern knee to the body, and this draws out a short but sweet firefight between the featherweights.
Nakamura plugs on with his elbow strikes, stringing them together rather than pitching one at a time.
Nakamura drives up a knee, and he catches Szalay cleanly in the sternum and gives him serious pause.

He finds his timing just when he needs, likely down on the scorecards even if he may be leading this round.Szalay attacks, and Nakamura drives a counter knee square into his jaw that separates the Aussie from his senses.
Szalay twirls around cinematically and hits the deck on his hands, dazed and confused while Dean is moment away from stepping in.

To finish the job, Nakamura leaps after his downed foe and whips his fists at his melon relentlessly, pummeling the Australian athlete until Dean has no choice but to intervene.What a knee, and what a comeback for the man from Japan.
In the blink of an eye, Nakamura has reversed his fortunes and hands "Seb" his first career stoppage loss when it mattered most.
The Official Result Keiichiro Nakamura def.
Sebastian Szalay R3 3:48 via TKO (Knee and Punches)

Kaan Ofli (145.25) vs.

Zha Yi (145.5) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Yi (-218), Ofli (+180) Round 1 The promotion itself handled the first three matches tonight differently, even going so far as to declare they were the Road to UFC 4 finals while the rest are UFC 325âfor Fight Finder purposes, we consider them all as UFC fights, and do not separate the two cards for record keeping.
Those out of the way, we move on to the reason most fans are here as Jon Anik takes over on the mic.
Giving locals someone to root for early, Ofli (12-4-1, 1-2 UFC) reps his home country against China's Yi (26-5, 1-2 UFC).
The third man in the Octagon will be referee Jim Perdios, and the featherweights touch 'em up before proceeding.
Yi gets right to the center of the cage, aiming his jab to the head and body and landing once to the latter.
Yi swipes out a right to the body, and Ofli replies with four speedy hooks.
Ofli punches his way into a takedown, and Yi slips out of the way and forces Ofli to abandon it.
Ofli keeps after Yi, belting him with a right hand and using a body lock to drag the fight down.
Yi flips him around, and the ensuing scramble between the energized athletes leads to Ofli winding up on top.
Yi tries to utilize butterfly hooks to keep Ofli off of him, and he even flirts with an armbar off his back, but it is all for naught when Ofli smashes him in the face with a vicious right hand.
Just like that, Yi turns to the side as he does not want to eat another one of those shots, and he leans on the fencing so that Ofli cannot take his back.
Yi postures in hopes of standing, and Ofli controls him and knees him flush to the body.
Yi is wrangled back to the canvas, with Ofli tripping the Chinese fighter up to keep him grounded.
Ofli clasps his hands around the waist, letting them go so he can wind up and smack Yi in the face with several left hands.
Yi ignores them and fights back to his feet, taking a couple knees to the stomach and an elbow that irritates him.
Yi breaks off, and Ofli chases after him with a push kick and a punch.
They loose hooks at the same time, with Ofli taking Yi off-balance with a ferocious hook.
Yi stumbles and gathers his thoughts, getting right back up but notably retreating.
Yi looks for a counter while Ofli is advancing, and Ofli falls over when landing a kick and takes a right hand on the way up.

Jonathan Micallef (170.25) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Micallef (-135), Elliott (+114) Round 1 Of the 10 fights the UFC designates as UFC 325, two of them do not feature an athlete from Oceania.

Wales as he locks horns with Elliott (12-3, 3-1 UFC).

Micallef lunges recklessly, landing a front kick but nearly falling over while doing so.

Jacob Malkoun (185.75) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Malkoun (-166), Finney (+140) Round 1 Aussies continue to populate the Octagon, as Malkoun (8-3, 4-3 UFC) reps Straya against one of the only Americans on the billing in undefeated fireplug Finney (11-0, 1-0 UFC).

Malkoun beats his man to the punch with another brief exchange, leading Finney to bullrush him and swing for the fences.

Finney loads up on counters, even catching Malkoun with a left hook, but Malkoun hurts him repeatedly.

He partially connects with one, and is met with a Teixeira knee on the way out.
Tuivasa ducks a telegraphed spinning back elbow and jabs the body to set up a right upstairs, and elbows Teixeira as well.
Teixeira answers with a thudding body kick, so Tuivasa kicks his legs hard.
Tuivasa's kicks are rapidly disrupting the taller man, so Teixeira gives him one or two back to think about.
Tuivasa keeps attacking the lead leg, shrugging off a straight right hand to deliver a huge right hand over the top.
Teixeira boots Tuivasa upside the head, and he shoots in for a double and bowls "Bam Bam" over.
Tuivasa clings to his man while seated up, and he turns the corner as his shorts fall down.
Teixeira is able to turn him back around and put him flat on his back, where he delivers a few elbows to Tuivasa before mounting him.
Teixeira uses 12-to-6 elbows when available, and uses heavy chest-to-chest pressure to keep Tuivasa stuck.
Tuivasa looks to his corner when controlled and shakes his head in frustration, and he gets flattened out on his stomach.
Teixeira pounds on him with his free left hand, and Tuivasa's slight head movement protects him from a few of the blows but most get through.
Tuivasa turns over to get to his back once more, with Teixeira back to mount looking to execute an Ezekiel choke.
Tuivasa breaks the choke grip while "Xicao" holds him down and beats on him.
Teixeira flirts with a straight armlock but is met with Tuivasa punches from his back until the second round concludes.
Fans boo Teixeira heartily.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Teixeira Brian Knapp scores the round: 10-9 Teixeira Tyler Treese scores the round: 10-9 Teixeira Round 3 Tuivasa hurries forward to offer a glove touch and start engaging, and he loads up quickly on leg kicks.
Tuivasa goes to the body with a left and follows it with a knee, and Teixeira backs him away with a front kick.
Tuivasa fakes with his right to open up a strike, and Teixeira answered with a labored takedown attempt that fails miserably.
Tuivasa shakes his head at him and loads up on a huge right hand, and Teixeira is feeling it but gets some respite when Tuivasa elects to clinch him.
Tuivasa knees the thigh when pressing on the Brazilian, with both fighters likely spent after about 12 minutes of fight thus far.
Tuivasa bails on it and starts swinging.
Teixeira backs away, stumbling as his balance is starting to betray him, and he nails Tuivasa with two punches coming in.
Tuivasa goes for broke with two huge punches, and he hurts Teixeira with them and proceeds to clinch him again.
The commentary booth is collectively losing it at Tuivasa's strategy, seemingly not realizing how exhausted both men are.
Tuivasa slashes his foe in the face with an elbow, and he takes a kick to the liver and puts his hands on his hips.
Teixeira does the same, and Tuivasa lumbers towards him and pulls his shorts up, before clinching again.
Tuivasa drapes his hands over the top of the cage, and is warned for it, so he starts ripping punches to the body.
Tuivasa fights in brief spurts before tying his man up, and he stings Teixeira with a pair of punches and stifles a rough takedown attempt.

The color commentators of Daniel Cormier and Michael Bisping are screaming advice to Tuivasa as if they were cornering him, and Tuivasa cannot hear them or does not have the energy to do anything about it.
He holds on from on top before working the body a few times, and when Teixeira scrambles, a sweaty Tuivasa slides over the back while swinging as hard as he can.
The horrid heavyweight slopfest ends after stunningly going 15 minutes, with both big men needing oxygen tanks after what they produced there.

Rafael Fiziev (155.5) vs.

Mauricio Ruffy (155.25) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Ruffy (-122), Fiziev (+102) Round 1 It's a striker's delight in the "featured fight of the night" slot, as lightweights in need of a big win lock 'em up.
"Ataman" Fiziev (13-4, 7-4 UFC) may have struggled having to face Justin Gaethje twice in the span of about two years, but he righted the ship last June by taking out Ignacio Bahamondes.
On the other side of the equation, Fighting Nerds staple Ruffy (12-2, 3-1 UFC) saw his mighty win streak come to a crashing halt last year when the co-headliner Benoit St.
Denis wrangled and tapped him.
This ranked lightweight contest where only man will remain in the top 10 when the dust settles will be officiated by referee Dan Movahedi.
The heavy hitters touch gloves before handling their business.
Ruffy in a wide stance holds the center of the cage, avoiding a sweeping low kick while keeping his lead hand dangerously low.
The head movement allows Ruffy to dodge a sudden head kick, and he answers with a quick leg kick.
Fiziev slowly works his way forward, cutting off the cage and darting in behind a single left hand.
Ruffy tosses out another kick, and Fiziev drills him with one that is far heavier.
Fiziev ducks away from a tie-up attempt and goes low with another hard kick.
Ruffy is not responding well to the calf kicks from the Tiger Muay Thai striking instructor, and Fiziev pressures him all the way to the wall to force a clinch.
Ruffy turns him around, and Fiziev is able to escape out the side and nail the body with a kick.
Ruffy offers a spinning elbow that is not accurate, and Fiziev walks him down without fear of reprisal.
Ruffy steps in to strike, and he gets caught with a pair of punches and a surprise head kick.
Fiziev keeps Ruffy on the back foot, whipping him with kicks to remain pinned to the wall.
Ruffy chains a low kick into a step-in knee, and Fiziev barely dodges in time.
Both men go to the body, with tit-for-tat powerful single striking exchanges.
Ruffy largely throws one at a time, while Fiziev walks through them and fires of his own combos.
The round ends.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Ruffy Brian Knapp scores the round: 10-9 Ruffy Tyler Treese scores the round: 10-9 Ruffy Round 2 The athletes meet in the middle, with Fiziev starting off with strong body kicks.
Ruffy replies with a solid right hand to back him off, and he spins with a back kick that Fiziev evades in time.
Fiziev kicks low and then to the ribs, and he ducks under a sweeping left hand.
Ruffy sneaks in a right hand over the top, and he partially checks a low kick.
Fiziev rushes in with a left hook, and he keeps his opponent skirting on the back wall.
They trade punches, with Fiziev taking a low kick on the way out that he does not defend well.
Ruffy prods out a few jabs and is met with a hard body kick, and he winds up with a huge right hand that Fiziev takes flush.
Fiziev spins with a wheel kick and bounces off, and he resets without Ruffy taking advantage of it.
Fiziev kicks at the front calf, and is answered with one from his opponent.
Fiziev digs a right to the midsection, and then ducks in to go left to the liver.
Ruffy retreats, and he takes low kicks on both sides.
Ruffy reaches out with a right, and he bats Fiziev upside the head with a standing back fist.
Fiziev walks Fiziev down and boots him in the liver again, and he gets backed off with a straight jab but is right in front of Ruffy.
Ruffy measures his man and blasts Fiziev in the face with a right hand down the pipe, and Fiziev goes squirrely and on ice skates trips around the cage barely able to stay upright.
Movahedi thinks to step in, but allows them to keep fighting.
Ruffy does not go wild, instead picking his shots and methodically clobbering Fiziev with ground strikes.

Fiziev still has his head on a swivel, and he sways and moves so that he can work his way back to his feet, but after several more blistering right hands, he is in a bad way as his balance has completely abandoned him.Ruffy is able to bully Fiziev down to the ground again, partly due to Fiziev clinging to consciousness with figurative stars over his head like a "Street Fighter" character, and he unloads with a brief but final, concussive bombardment of punches until Movahedi does intervene.This is a huge triumph for Ruffy, earning easily the biggest win of his career by putting away a renowned muay thai striker and trainer.
The Official Result Mauricio Ruffy def.
Rafael Fiziev R2 4:30 via TKO (Punches)
